    "plan_content": "Here's the complete plan I've designed:\n\n---\n\n## Plan: Add `next/geo` Utility Module\n\n**5 file changes** — 4 new, 1 modified. All follow the exact patterns of the existing `next/server` / `userAgent` implementation.\n\n### Files to create\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.ts` | Core implementation |\n| `packages/next/geo.js` | Public CJS entry point |\n| `packages/next/geo.d.ts` | TypeScript type re-exports |\n| `packages/next/src/server/web/spec-extension/geo.test.ts` | Unit tests |\n\n### File to modify\n- `packages/next/package.json` — insert `\"geo.js\"` and `\"geo.d.ts\"` into the `files` array after `\"form.d.ts\"` (alphabetical position)\n\n### Key implementation decisions\n\n1. **`geoFromHeaders`** uses `headers.get('x-vercel-ip-country') || headers.get('cf-ipcountry') || undefined` — Vercel takes precedence, Cloudflare is the fallback; `|| undefined` converts `null` to `undefined` for all optional fields\n\n2. **`country`** is derived from `COUNTRY_NAMES[countryCode.toUpperCase()]` so it stays `undefined` for unknown codes rather than throwing\n\n3. **`isInRegion`** does `.toLowerCase()` comparison on both sides for case-insensitivity\n\n4. **`geoDistance`** uses the standard Haversine formula with Earth radius 6371 km\n\n5. **Tests** use `node:test` + `node:assert/strict` (Node.js 18+ built-ins, no external framework); NY→London test checks for 5520–5620 km range\n\n### Verification steps\n```bash\npnpm --filter=next types                  # TypeScript check (~10s)\npnpm --filter=next build                  # Build to dist/\nnode --test .../geo.test.ts               # Run unit tests\n```",
